# Companion Satellite for Linux

This archive contains a desktop build of Companion Satellite. There are two ways
to set it up:

1. Desktop installation (recommended)

   Run the included installer:
   $ ./install.sh

   It can install either system-wide (to /opt/companion-satellite, asking for
   your administrator password) or just for the current user (to
   ~/.local/share/companion-satellite). The installer:
   - copies this build to the chosen location,
   - adds Companion Satellite to your application menu with an icon,
   - installs the udev rules so it can access USB surfaces (see below),
   - checks for the required system libraries.

   You can also pass --system or --user to skip the prompt, and --force to
   overwrite an existing install.

   Once installed it appears in your application menu, or you can launch it
   directly with /opt/companion-satellite/companion-satellite (or the
   equivalent path under ~/.local/share for a user install).

2. Headless / server installation

   If you want to run Satellite on a headless machine, use the install script,
   which sets up and manages dependencies, udev rules and updates for you:
   $ curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/bitfocus/companion-satellite/main/pi-image/install.sh | bash

   See the repository at https://github.com/bitfocus/companion-satellite for
   more details.

## Required dependencies

Companion Satellite needs a few system libraries that aren't installed by
default on some Debian and Ubuntu systems. install.sh checks for them, but you
can install them yourself with:

$ sudo apt-get update
$ sudo apt-get install -y libusb-1.0-0-dev libudev-dev libfontconfig1

## Udev rules (USB device access)

For Satellite to access your Stream Decks, Loupedecks, X-keys or other supported
USB surfaces, some udev rules must be installed. install.sh does this for you,
but if you skipped that step or want to do it manually, run as root:

$ cp 50-satellite-desktop.rules /etc/udev/rules.d/50-satellite-desktop.rules
$ udevadm control --reload-rules
$ udevadm trigger

Then replug any USB devices Satellite should be able to use. These desktop rules
use uaccess, so the logged-in user is granted access automatically - there is no
group to join and no need to log out and back in.

(For headless/server setups there is also a 50-satellite.rules file, which grants
access via a dedicated `satellite` group instead of the current user session - the
headless install script uses that one.)

These rules occasionally change as support for new devices is added, so it's
worth re-running install.sh (or repeating the steps above) when you update
Satellite.

## Troubleshooting

If launching fails with a GTK 2/3 vs GTK 4 error, append --gtk-version=3 to the
launch command.
